Preheat your oven to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Chop the @potatoes{450%g} into 2cm wide wedges (no need to peel). Pop them onto a
large #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{}, season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then
toss to coat.

Spread out in a single layer.
> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden, ~{25-35%minutes}.
Turn halfway through.

Meanwhile, cut the @mature cheddar cheese{30%g} in half widthways. Peel and
grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}).

In a large #bowl{}, combine the @sun-dried tomato paste{25%g}, garlic and
@panko breadcrumbs{10%g}, then add the @British beef mince{240%g}. Season with
salt and pepper, then mix together with your hands.

Roll the mince into even-sized balls. Shape into 2cm thick burgers around a
chunk of cheese, ensuring they're well sealed, 1 per person.
> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw mince.

Pop the burgers onto a #baking tray{} and bake on the middle shelf of your
oven until cooked through, ~{12-15%minutes}.
> IMPORTANT: The mince is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

While the burgers cook, chop the @medium tomato{1} into 2cm pieces.

Put the @balsamic glaze{12%ml} and @olive oil{1}(for the dressing) in a medium
bowl. Season with salt and pepper, then add the tomatoes and mix to combine.
Set aside for now.

When the wedges and burgers are almost cooked, halve the @burger buns{2}.

Pop onto a baking tray and into the oven to warm through, ~{2-3%minutes}.

When everything's ready, pop the buns on your plates and spread a little
@mayonnaise{2%tbsp}(see pantry for amount) over the cut sides. Fill with a
burger and a handful of @baby leaf mix{50%g}.
> TIP: Scoop up any escaped cheese from the baking tray and pile on top.

Add the remaining baby leaves to the tomato bowl and toss to coat.

Serve your melt in the middle burgers with the wedges and salad alongside.

Enjoy!